          <div>
            <p style="color:var(--islamic-green-light);font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:2px;margin-bottom:10px">☽ ISLAMIC HADITH</p>
            <p>Multiple hadith state the Mahdi will initially have <strong>313 core supporters</strong> — deliberately equated with the number of Muslims at the Battle of Badr, Islam's first and most miraculous military victory. A tiny faithful group defeats overwhelming opposition through divine help.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p style="color:var(--biblical-blue-light);font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:2px;margin-bottom:10px">✝ BIBLE — JUDGES 7</p>
            <p>God tells Gideon to reduce his army from 32,000 to <strong>300 men</strong> before attacking the Midianites — an overwhelming force. The tiny remnant wins by divine intervention, not military strength. Also: Revelation 7 — 144,000 sealed servants of God (exact multiples of 12, symbolic of completeness).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="margin-top:16px;color:var(--text-dim);font-style:italic;font-size:14px">Both traditions deliberately use a small, specific number of faithful to signal divine election and miraculous victory over overwhelming odds. The pattern — not the exact number — is theologically identical: God wins through the few, not the many.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 8: SUN RISING FROM THE WEST -->
